<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1894-08-07T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1894-08-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="43" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d43">
                    <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Denby</persName>, chargé, to
                            Mr. <persName type="to">Gresham</persName>.</hi></head>
                    <opener>
                        <seg rendition="#left">No. 44.]</seg>
                        <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the
                                    United States</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Pelting</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1894-08-07"><hi rend="italic">August 7, 1894</hi></date>.
                            (Received September 22.)</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to report that I received
                        to-day a telegram from Consul Fowler, Ningpo, stating that the Taotai
                        persists in closing the port to all ships.</p>
                    <p>As Japan, however, has given no pledge not to attack Ningpo, I have
                        telegraphed him in reply that this legation “can not object to China’s
                        necessary defensive measures.”</p>
                    <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                    <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Chas. Denby</hi>, Jr.</signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>